,"speaker":"Emtithal Mahmoud","title":"A young poet tells the story of Darfur","duration":651.0,"slug":"emtithal_mahmoud_a_young_poet_tells_the_story_of_darfur","viewed_count":940694},{"id":"652","hero":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/talkstar-photos/uploads/8953d163-926f-4331-8f1f-86db90b94f0b/ChimamandaAdichie_2009G-embed.jpg","speaker":"Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie","title":"The danger of a single story","duration":1129.0,"slug":"chimamanda_adichie_the_danger_of_a_single_story","viewed_count":15310270},{"id":"3362","hero":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/talkstar-photos/uploads/be4393c6-1c8f-442e-bb76-bd9385890000/GusCaselyHayford_2017G-embed.jpg","speaker":"Gus Casely-Hayford","title":"The powerful stories that shaped Africa","duration":1194.0,"slug":"gus_casely_hayford_the_powerful_stories_that_shaped_africa","viewed_count":1133675},{"id":"2891","hero":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/talkstar-photos/uploads/8d8572db-1081-4102-8105-63e00819024e/ChikaEzeanyaEsiobu_2017G-embed.jpg","speaker":"Chika Ezeanya-Esiobu","title":"How Africa can use its traditional knowledge to make progress","duration":849.0,"slug":"chika_ezeanya_esiobu_how_africa_can_use_its_traditional_knowledge_to_make_progress","viewed_count":1088868},{"id":"2881","hero":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/talkstar-photos/uploads/4dd984fe-3dfc-46da-8bb1-0b1e442855bc/OlufemiTaiwo_2017G-embed.jpg","speaker":"Olúfẹ́mi Táíwò","title":"Why Africa must become a center of knowledge again","duration":810.0,"slug":"oluf_mi_taiwo_why_africa_must_become_a_center_of_knowledge_again","viewed_count":1035986}],"slug":"nnedi_okorafor_sci_fi_stories_that_imagine_a_future_africa","speakers":[{"id":"3506","slug":"nnedi_okorafor","is_published":true,"firstname":"Nnedi","lastname":"Okorafor","middleinitial":"","title":"","description":"Science fiction writer","photo_url":"https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/4bc0a77cf3e21405258212a5a76deaa95512010a_254x191.jpg","whatotherssay":"","whotheyare":"Nnedi Okorafor weaves African cultures into the evocative settings and memorable characters of her science fiction work for kids and adults.","whylisten":"<p>Nnedi Okorafor is an award-winning novelist of African-based science fiction, fantasy and magical realism. Born in the US to Nigerian immigrant parents, Okorafor is known for weaving African cultures into creative settings and memorable characters. Her books include <em>Lagoon</em> (a British Science Fiction Association Award finalist for best novel), <em>Who Fears Death</em> (a World Fantasy Award winner for best novel), <em>Kabu Kabu</em> (a <em>Publisher&#39;s Weekly</em> best book for Fall 2013), <em>Akata Witch</em> (an Amazon.com best book of the year), <em>Zahrah the Windseeker</em> (winner of the Wole Soyinka Prize for African Literature) and <em>The Shadow Speaker</em> (a CBS Parallax Award winner).<br /><br />Her 2016 novel <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0756410789/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=teco06-20&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;creativeASIN=0756410789&amp;linkId=77781047fca16371e32b4ab89508cb26\" target=\"_blank\"><em>The Book of Phoenix</em></a> is an Arthur C. Clarke Award finalist, while the <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00Y7RWXHU/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=teco06-20&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;creativeASIN=B00Y7RWXHU&amp;linkId=aed54b58e40c381015415267656b68a4\" target=\"_blank\">first book in the Binti Trilogy</a> won both the Hugo and Nebula Awards for Best Novella. Her children&rsquo;s book <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0993225306/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=teco06-20&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;creativeASIN=0993225306&amp;linkId=770430cac175620635fc3230d1b2726b\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Chicken in the Kitchen</em></a> won an Africana Book Award. The final installment of the Binti Trilogy, titled <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B06WPBWQMM/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=teco06-20&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;creativeASIN=B06WPBWQMM&amp;linkId=4ca61aea66185865bf830618e953fb26\" target=\"_blank\"><em>The Night Masquerade</em></a>, will be released in September 2017, and the sequel to <em>Akata Witch</em> (titled <em>Akata Warrior</em>) is was published in October 2017. Meanwhile, her book <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0756406692/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=teco06-20&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;creativeASIN=0756406692&amp;linkId=3e3bf5e103f83076dee053db6805b5ad\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Who Fears Death</em></a> has been <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Nnedi/status/884454933554237441?\" target=\"_blank\">optioned by HBO</a>, with <em>Game of Thrones</em>&#39; George R.R. Martin as executive producer.</p><p>Okorafor is a full professor at the University at Buffalo, New York (SUNY).</p>"}],"speaker_name":"Nnedi Okorafor","tags":["creativity","Africa","adventure","science fiction","future","writing","identity","society"],"title":"Sci-fi stories that imagine a future Africa","video_type":{"id":"1","name":"TED Stage Talk"},"viewed_count":946613}]}
